Single Responsibility Principle states that a class should have only one reason to change.
The focus is not on the number of methods but on the responsibility the class represents. For example, a CreditApprovalService should only contain logic related to credit evaluation and approval.
 If email notification, auditing, logging, or other unrelated concerns are added to the same class, the class now changes for multiple reasons, violating SRP.
 In Spring applications, business services should also remain independent of web concerns such as ResponseEntity, which should be handled at the controller layer. Cross-cutting concerns like auditing and logging are typically implemented using AOP or dedicated components to keep responsibilities separated.


class CreditApprovalService {

    public CreditScore calculateScore() {}

    public boolean isEligible(Customer customer) {}

    public ApprovalResult approve(Customer customer) {}
}

